If $f''(x) > 0$ on $(a,b)$,then $f$ is convex on $(a,b)$ Proof:

Let $x_1,x_2 \in (a,b)$ with $x_1 \neq x_2$. Define $g \in C[0,1]$

$g(\theta) = f(\theta_{x_1} + (1-\theta)_{x_2}) - \theta f(x_1) - (1- \theta)f(x_2), \theta \in [0,1]$

we want to show $g \le 0$ as this will prove convexity. Direct calculation: $g(0) = g(1) = 0$ and $$
g''(\theta) = (x_1-x_2)^2f''(\thetax_1 + (1-\theta)x_2)
$$ 

suppose for contraition sake, $g>0$ somwhere on $[0,1]$

Maximum theorem: $g$ attains its (positive) maximum at $\theta_0 \in (0,1)$
Fermats_Theorem $\implies$ $g'(\theta_0) = 0$ By our assumption, $g''(\theta_0) >0$ so it is a local minimum. So $\theta_0$ is a local minimum and local maximum of $g$. Only possible if $g = constant$ but then $g'' = 0$ and $g'=0$ which is a contradiction.


